{"_type":"item","id":"019ea4fcc6877cc7ae826a5d56aec737","type":"discussion","status":"active","title":"Recut codetools skills around ephemeral-vs-durable: Basic (tiny scripts) vs Advanced (disciplined durable engineering)","description":"## Why this discussion\nHeavy owner+agent shaping of the recut codetools seeded skills (current scaffolds: minerva_codetools_coding / _advanced_coding / _plugin_authoring). The owner reviewed skill 1's content (via a Minerva note) and found it mis-framed. Capturing the philosophy here BEFORE filing the DCR + work_items to rewrite, so the reasoning stays attached to the resulting work. (Provenance for the eventual skill-rewrite DCR.)\n\n## The reframe (owner's note on skill 1)\nThe 'Coding' skill was built from a repo/codebase mental model (semantic index, locate symbols, navigate, buffered reviewable edits). That is the WRONG framing for the basic skill. Basic coding = tiny, throwaway, single-shot: 'write me Fibonacci / Hello-World / a quick transform' — write a small script (shell/Python/etc.), run it, read the output, hand back the result. Rarely >1000 lines, almost never a repo, no exploration, no index.\n\n## The clarifying axis: EPHEMERAL vs DURABLE\n- Basic = ephemeral: throwaway script, run it, return the answer. No tracking, no ceremony, no delegation, no repo. Optimized for speed.\n- Advanced = durable: real work that must survive and be trusted — so it is tracked (docket), done safely (risk discipline), scaled (sub-agents) when big.\nThis axis (not 'small vs large') is what makes docket/risks/sub-agents principled inclusions in Advanced rather than a grab-bag.\n\n## Decision: 3 skills, Advanced absorbs repo work (owner)\nBasic Coding (tiny scripts) / Advanced Coding (real-codebase: navigate + edit + debug + research + visualize + process discipline) / Plugin authoring. Keep 3 (no 4th). Manage Advanced's large surface with a MODAL system prompt (navigate/edit · debug · research · visualize · track-work · delegate), pin the union of tools, prompt gates when each mode fires.\n\n## Basic Coding — drafted rewrite\n- id: minerva_codetools_basic_coding (rename from _coding — TBD)\n- title: 'Basic coding — write, run, and return a small script'\n- summary: Quick, self-contained coding: write a short script, run it, return the result. One-off requests (function/calculation/Hello-World/Fibonacci). No repo, index, or exploration.\n- system_prompt: small self-contained coding to answer a concrete request; short script, rarely a repo; do NOT index/explore/navigate; loop = write file -> execute -> read output -> fix-and-rerun -> deliver; smallest thing that answers it; if it needs a real codebase, hand off to the larger codebase-coding mode (escalation phrased by CONDITION, not by sibling name — per owner's earlier C6 note 'skills shouldn't reference other skills directly').\n- preconditions: user wants a small standalone task now; no repo/index assumed.\n- outcome: small script written + executed; result verified + delivered; script left in editor.\n- steps: 0 scope+pick scratch path; 1 file_write; 2 bash to execute (capture stdout+stderr); 3 file_edit + rerun on error; 4 (opt) file_read outputs; 5 deliver.\n- tool_deps: file_write, file_edit, file_read, bash (down from 14). Dropped: stale_check, analyze, query, get_context, describe_symbol, grep, glob, get_diff, journal_mark. No validate, no cwd (use /tmp absolute paths).\n\n## Advanced Coding — the disciplined-engineering methodology (the meat)\nSystem prompt encodes a METHODOLOGY, not just tools. The loop:\n1. Frame — capture work in docket with a Definition of Done (the in/out contract).\n2. Survey before writing — RE-USE MAP (what to reuse, DRY mitigation) + FILE PRE-FACTOR (files you have vs need). Owner: these working artifacts go in small NOTES.\n3. Design — pseudo-code the algorithm first (in a small NOTE).\n4. Build — small scoped changes, reuse mapped seams, match surrounding style/quality.\n5. Verify — tests / validate / review diff.\n6. Land — commit WIPs (per-file git add, co-author trailer, branch hygiene); USER decides when to push; update docket state.\n- Risk discipline throughout: verify branch/HEAD before commit; firewall scope creep into NEW docket items (DoD must not silently grow); dup-check for DRY; never force-push / --no-verify.\n- PROPORTIONALITY guardrail (load-bearing): scale the discipline to the task — a typo fix skips notes/pseudo-code/docket; a multi-file feature gets the full loop. Otherwise the skill is bureaucratic.\n- Anchor in the owner's RUBRIC: durability > DRY > reliability > well-factored > readability > cost. The re-use map = DRY, pre-factor = well-factored, pseudo-code = reliability — the rubric applied before code exists.\n\n## Knowledge & tracking decision rules (Advanced must TEACH these)\nNOTES (immediate, this-task-only, small, discard after): pseudo-code, file pre-factor list, API research ('use X this way' for this change).\nDOCKET (outlives the task) — the test: 'needed only to finish this task?' -> note; 'useful after it ships?' -> docket. Pick the type:\n- shaping a problem/want with the user (philosophy, unsettled) -> discussion (active->resolved; on resolve, spawns+links the dcr/work_items — provenance). Rare; triggered by heavy dialogue or explicit user ask. (THIS item is an example.)\n- new design direction -> dcr\n- defined unit of work -> work_item / bug\n- root cause -> rca\n- reusable incantation/path/gotcha -> hint\n- how-a-subsystem-works reference -> kb\n- non-obvious realization -> insight\nAPI research example of the split: 'use X for this change' -> note; 'how library X actually works' (reusable) -> kb.\n\n## Docket-project decision rules (Advanced must TEACH these)\n- Default to master (a fresh user has only master).\n- On entering a codebase, look for an existing project FIRST: glob *.dct (often gitignored, e.g. Docs/<name>.dct) -> docket_project_list -> attach/use it instead of master. Surface which project ('Found project foo, tracking there').\n- New project = an ongoing, distinct body of work with its own backlog (not a one-off). Creating one is user-facing/structural -> PROPOSE, don't auto-create.\n- Applied live: codetools has NO own .dct (none in minerva-plugins); loaded projects = minerva-services(MIN,primary)/cad/minerva(MNR). Codetools history lives in minerva, so this discussion was filed there; graduating codetools to its own project is a separate proposable decision (would fragment lineage — deferred).\n\n## Decisions still open\n1. note-vs-docket test + type table — confirm shape (owner leaning yes).\n2. project creation = always ASK (vs auto when confident) — agent leans ask.\n3. rename Basic id _coding -> _basic_coding?\n4. sub-agents = DEFERRED to v1 (least-proven, heaviest tool pull); add after the rest is HITL'd.\n\n## Next (on resolution)\nLock Basic into codetools/manifest.json; draft Advanced's modal system prompt around the methodology above; update Advanced tool_deps to absorb repo-nav (stale_check/analyze/query/get_context/describe_symbol/grep/glob/get_diff/journal_mark/file_* + docket_* ) on top of inspect/get_graph/explore/research/viz. Then HITL each skill in focused chats. Spawns: a skill-rewrite DCR or work_items linked back to this discussion.","created_at":"2026-06-08T02:08:09","updated_at":"2026-06-08T03:32:18","priority":2,"tags":["codetools","discussion","shaping","skills","ux"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019ea523295175f2b7e9a0005dfc2e78","type":"dcr","status":"proposed","title":"Plugins seed knowledge (kb/hint) alongside skills, referenced by stable key","description":"## Motivation\nSkills MUST be self-contained: a seeded skill cannot reference a docket item by id, because an end-user who installs the plugin may not have the project that item lives in (verified constraint, codetools skills recut). Today the only durable knowledge a plugin ships is its skills — install seeds manifest.skills[] only (PluginManager.install_plugin -> _seed_plugin_skills; no kb/hint/knowledge path exists, grep-confirmed). So all substrate depth has to be crammed inline into skill system_prompts, which bloats them and prevents the browsable/queryable/updatable knowledge layer the rest of docket provides.\n\n## Proposal\nAdd a manifest `knowledge[]` array (kb + hint types; possibly insight) seeded into the user docket on install, PARALLEL to skills[]. The seeding apparatus already generalizes — reuse the skills machinery:\n- PluginManager._seed_plugin_skills / _unseed_plugin_skills -> a knowledge equivalent.\n- PluginSkillRecord (per-item provenance: which plugin shipped it, pristine content for diff, customised flag) -> PluginKnowledgeRecord.\n- The seed-consent dialog (PluginSkillSeedDialog) -> include knowledge items.\n- Unseed-on-remove keeping user-customized items (the kept-ids pattern).\n\n## Key design decisions\n1. STABLE-KEY references. Seeded items get a fresh ULID per install, so a skill cannot reference a kb by id. Knowledge items carry a manifest-assigned stable `key` (docket items already have a `key` field); skills reference kbs by key, resolved at use-time. This keeps skills self-sufficient (the kb is browsable DEPTH, never a hard dependency) while letting them point to more.\n2. TARGET PROJECT. Where seeded knowledge lands — master (default), or a plugin-scoped/component-scoped project. Ties to the docket-project decisions (a fresh user has only master; codetools work now lives in the shared `plugins` project, component=codetools).\n3. LIFECYCLE parity with skills: re-seed on reinstall (reload != reinstall); keep user-edited items on remove; pristine-hash diff to detect upstream changes.\n4. SCOPE of types: kb + hint first (reference + actionable gotcha). insight/discussion likely out (those are author-side, not shippable).\n\n## Consequences\n- Skills stay lean + self-contained; plugins ship the full knowledge taxonomy we designed (kb = how a subsystem works; hint = reusable gotcha), not just skills.\n- The annotation-substrate extension knowledge (and the 7 plugin-substrate trap-families) could ship as kbs the plugin-authoring skill points to by key, instead of being fully inlined.\n\n## Non-goals\nNot changing the skills mechanism itself; not seeding work_items/bugs/dcrs (those are work, not shipped knowledge); not auto-creating projects (propose-don't-auto stands).\n\n## Provenance\nSpun out of the codetools skills-recut discussion (plugins:019ea4fcc687) while shaping the self-contained plugin-authoring skill. For v1 the plugin-authoring skill is self-contained (knowledge embedded inline); this DCR is the path to lift that depth into shipped, browsable kbs later.","created_at":"2026-06-08T02:50:05","updated_at":"2026-06-08T02:50:17","priority":3,"tags":["dcr","docket","knowledge","plugins","seeding","substrate"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb4b8d3e27dfcbd90093478cec5e2","type":"work_item","status":"backlog","title":"Migrate codetools/internal/bridge onto shared/ (near-identical fork)","description":"Found during the shared/ extraction review (2026-06-10, minerva-plugins): codetools/internal/bridge is a pre-existing near-identical fork of the bridge that now lives in shared/bridge — framing.go is byte-identical; worker.go differs only in naming and already has the module parameter the shared version gained.\n\nMigrate codetools to import github.com/imrans-lab/minerva-plugins/shared/bridge (same prefix codetools already uses), delete codetools/internal/bridge, verify go build/vet/test green and the codetools binary builds. Reference: cad/go.mod's require+replace pattern (replace => ../shared) and cad's import updates from the extraction commit.\n\nDRY trigger source: reviewer note on the shared-module extraction round (MNR item 019eb47f71b5).","created_at":"2026-06-11T03:27:52","updated_at":"2026-06-11T04:18:57","priority":3,"tags":["codetools","dry","go","shared"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb4e4028e751eb809bc71f48593f5","type":"work_item","status":"backlog","title":"Extract shared MCP router loop (cad + pcb duplicate it)","description":"pcb/main.go's JSON-RPC dispatch loop, envelope types, and internal/tools registry are byte-similar to cad's — an intentional, declared copy in the scaffold round (2026-06-10) because extraction wasn't justified by one consumer. Two consumers now exist; three after codetools migrates onto shared/bridge (PLG 019eb4b8d3e2 — natural companion item).\n\nDesign note from the scaffold round: the handler signatures deliberately differ — cad's is (ctx, *bridge.Worker, params), pcb's is (ctx, params) (no worker yet; gains one in the worker round). A shared router must parameterize over the worker dependency (generic handler context or closure-injection) rather than forcing every plugin to carry a Worker.\n\nScope: shared/mcpserver (or shared/router) package — stdio loop, initialize/tools/list/tools/call/shutdown, notification tolerance, registry; cad + pcb consume it. Verify: go build/vet/test all modules; Minerva smoke tests (cad 37, pcb 30) stay green.","created_at":"2026-06-11T04:15:02","updated_at":"2026-06-11T04:18:57","priority":3,"tags":["dry","go","router","shared"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eafbe3360760b818b45fd663a2922","type":"work_item","status":"backlog","title":"agent-relay plugin (Phase B of Minerva DCR 019eafbdcfb3)","description":"Tracking item establishing the agent-relay component. Full phase plan lives in the Minerva-docket DCR 019eafbdcfb37c509a578be8a77095df (Phase B section): B1 scaffold (Rust subprocess, manifest tools minerva_agent_relay_watch_start/stop/status + read_clean + profiles_list), B2 chrome filter, B3 per-CLI turn-detection profiles, B4 distill+deliver, B5 tests/HITL, B6 marketplace packaging (regen_registry.py PLUGIN_DIRS allow-list). Hard constraints: no FCIBs, never modify agent CLI user configs. Prototype path before substrate lands: mcp.proxy:minerva_terminal_* grants.","created_at":"2026-06-10T04:15:38","updated_at":"2026-06-10T04:15:38","priority":2,"tags":["agent-relay","marketplace","scaffold"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eafd4e71476ae9247e4347b3755bc","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"B1: Scaffold agent-relay plugin (manifest, Rust worker, tool surface)","description":"manifest.json tools (source of truth — every tool listed or Minerva won't expose it; declare FULL nested arg schemas or Minerva stringifies them):\nminerva_agent_relay_watch_start (terminal_id, profile, notify_mode: armed|all_turns|none) / watch_stop / watch_status (reports armed state, last detection method, exchange counts, truncation flags),\nminerva_agent_relay_send (write via host.terminal.write + arm ONE-SHOT wake — DCR comment #466),\nminerva_agent_relay_read_clean (base chrome filter + installed rules + inline ad-hoc patterns),\nminerva_agent_relay_read_turn (distilled via host.providers.chat),\nminerva_agent_relay_filter_set/filter_list/filter_delete, minerva_agent_relay_profile_get/profile_set, minerva_agent_relay_profiles_list.\nEvent: agent_relay.turn_completed payload {terminal_id, kind: turn_completed|input_requested|agent_exited|terminal_closed|timed_out, detection: bell|settle_prompt|prompt_marker|child_exit|timeout}.\nCapabilities: host.terminal.* (A2), host.providers.chat, host.notify, mcp.proxy: minerva_create_note, minerva_link_note_to_chat, minerva_speak.\nTests: manifest validates (tool-prefix rule enforced PluginDefinition.gd:322), plugin installs + starts, tools visible after /mcp reconnect (known gotcha), declared-event validation clean (reinstall to clear stale plugins.json records).","created_at":"2026-06-10T04:40:26","updated_at":"2026-06-10T05:45:49","priority":2,"tags":["agent-relay","phase-b","scaffold"],"parent":"plugins.dct:019eafbe3360760b818b45fd663a2922","resolution":"Shipped @ plugins main cefe66f (work-cycle Sonnet, audited: ancestry OK, scope = agent-relay/ + .gitignore only; cargo build+test re-verified independently, 18/18; manifest valid JSON, 12 tools, 8 capability grants, agent_relay.turn_completed event declared). Scansort Rust subprocess shape; chrome_filter.rs pure fn with 12 unit fixtures (box-drawing line drop, border-column strip, blank collapse, braille spinners deliberately NOT dropped — B3's job). DEVIATION (accepted): brief said 5 tools, worker declared 12 — the extras (send, read_turn, filter_set/list/delete, profile_get/set) are exactly the DCR #464/#466 shaped surface, pre-declared as not_implemented stubs so B2-B4 fill handlers instead of re-touching the manifest (each schema change costs a /mcp reconnect — fewer manifest edits is the right trade). profiles_list returns claude/codex/opencode seeds marked \"calibration pending\"."}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eafd508487353bea84d19c2fd58ef","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"B2: Chrome filter + read_clean (base layer, redaction defaults, honest truncation)","description":"Base layer (always on): drop lines that are solely U+2500–U+25FF/punctuation runs; strip border columns (│┃ + inner padding); collapse consecutive duplicate lines; squeeze 3+ blanks to 1. Rule layer: profile-scope (persisted, per CLI) + session-scope (per terminal) regex strip/replace, applied after base; inline per-call patterns for experimentation (comment #464). Default redaction rules (risk #5): common key/token shapes (AWS, bearer, PEM headers) — replace with [REDACTED]. Honest truncation (risk #7): result carries truncated flag + rows dropped when scrollback overflowed the read window; reads are viewport+recent-scrollback at turn end, not purist delta.\nTest plan: golden-output unit tests against RECORDED screen fixtures from real claude/codex/opencode sessions (capture fixtures early — they also drive B3); rule precedence (base→profile→session→inline); redaction patterns; truncation flag on synthetic overflow.","created_at":"2026-06-10T04:40:34","updated_at":"2026-06-10T06:05:58","priority":2,"tags":["agent-relay","filter","phase-b"],"parent":"plugins.dct:019eafbe3360760b818b45fd663a2922","resolution":"Shipped @ plugins main 1cb44ad (work-cycle Sonnet, audited: ancestry OK, scope agent-relay/ only, 70/70 cargo tests re-verified independently). Runtime filter rules (filter_set/list/delete, regex validated at set time, applied after built-in chrome pass — DCR #464 surface live); 9-kind redaction pass ON by default (aws/github/openai-style/slack tokens, PEM blocks, credential= values, bearer headers) with read_clean redact:bool declared in manifest (input_schema key); honest truncation 30000-char cap keeping the TAIL on newline boundary with truncated+omitted_chars always present; 3 per-CLI golden fixtures marked \"synthetic — replace with real captures during B5 HITL\". Fixtures contain no secret-shaped strings."}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eafd52b0c7f1299dbdc1e10b86435","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"B3: Turn detection — per-CLI profiles, arming, wake causes","description":"Watch loop on host.terminal.wait long-poll. Default shipped profiles: claude, codex, opencode — each {prompt_box regex, busy/spinner glyphs, permission-dialog regex, alt_screen flag (viewport reads, no scrollback delta), bell_capable, settle_ms, arm_timeout_ms}; runtime-overridable via profile_set (comment #464). Detection precedence: bell (if capable) > settle+prompt-box-visible+spinners-absent. Kind classification (risk #2 → feature): permission-dialog pattern → input_requested; idle prompt → turn_completed; shell-prompt markers ([888z) during active watch → agent_exited (hint minerva-terminal/exit-detection-layers); wait cause terminal_closed → terminal_closed; arm timeout → timed_out with current screen attached. Arming: only agent_relay_send arms (one-shot); human keystrokes and core terminal_write never arm; notify_mode all_turns/none per watch_start (comment #466). NON-INTERFERENCE (comment #465): observation only — no probe sequences, no scroll_viewport, no focus.\nTest plan: detection classification matrix replayed against recorded VT-stream fixtures per CLI (turn end, permission prompt, agent quit, segfault, long silent compile); armed vs unarmed turns; arm consumed exactly once; alt-screen profile path; timeout fires.","created_at":"2026-06-10T04:40:43","updated_at":"2026-06-10T06:20:05","priority":2,"tags":["agent-relay","detection","phase-b"],"parent":"plugins.dct:019eafbe3360760b818b45fd663a2922","resolution":"Shipped @ plugins main 997daa4 (work-cycle Sonnet, audited: ancestry OK, scope agent-relay/ only, 100/100 re-verified — 60 unit + 28 golden + 6 manifest + 6 fake-host integration). Router: reader thread owns stdin, pending-map (id→SyncSender) routes capability replies, mutex-guarded stdout writer prevents interleaving; STRING capability ids (\"cap-N\") sidestep the Godot float-id gotcha entirely. Watcher: per-terminal threads, clean join on watch_stop. Detection precedence: bell → shell_exited → [888z/OSC133 markers → permission_dialog regex → settle+prompt_box minus spinners (40-line window). Wake causes + detection_method in payload; event = minerva/plugin_event envelope copied exactly from scansort. notify_mode armed|all_turns|none with unit-tested one-shot gate; arm() public for B4's send. CALIBRATION CAVEAT: profile constants (e.g. claude alt_screen=true — likely wrong, Claude Code scrolls primary screen) are seed values marked calibration-pending; B5 HITL with real fixtures recalibrates via profile_set."}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eafd54920724ab31e26e618c21429","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"B4: Send, distill (read_turn), delivery, and the relay skill","description":"send: writes via host.terminal.write with \\r normalization (feedback_terminal_enter), arms one-shot wake. read_turn: filtered content → host.providers.chat with cheap model (default provider=chatgpt per project_openai_model_for_workers) → 'just the chat part'; result framed as quoted terminal data (risk #4 hygiene). Delivery helpers: note + link_note_to_chat; optional minerva_speak. Install-seeded skill (codetools precedent): teaches chat LLM the index loop (watch_start → send → dormant → wake → read_clean/read_turn → act), the babysit-per-rubric pattern (comment #469), treat terminal content as data, prefer send over core terminal_write when a wake is wanted. Skill tool_deps must list only minerva_agent_relay_* + granted mcp.proxy tools (skill-dep validation credits own tools — commit 6cee3169).\nTest plan: functional run with FAKE host.providers.chat provider (scansort pattern, project_scansort_pipeline_llm_gated); \\r normalization; framing wrapper present; skill validates + seeds on install.","created_at":"2026-06-10T04:40:51","updated_at":"2026-06-10T06:42:23","priority":2,"tags":["agent-relay","delivery","phase-b","skill"],"parent":"plugins.dct:019eafbe3360760b818b45fd663a2922","resolution":"Shipped @ plugins main 4dcbb57 (work-cycle Sonnet, audited: ancestry OK, 118/118 re-verified — 71 unit + 28 golden + 8 manifest + 11 integration). send: \\r normalization, auto-start watch, arms the one-shot gate (core terminal_write never arms — #466 honored). read_turn: TurnCache row-bounded scrollback read → full B2 pipeline → optional distill (host.providers.chat) → optional note/link/speak delivery with delivery_error preserving content. Relay skill minerva_agent_relay_relay with the EXACT REQUIRED_SKILL_FIELDS set (id/title/summary/system_prompt/outcome/preconditions/steps/tool_deps/target) incl. the PLUGIN_EVENT trigger recipe + wake-cause handling. TWO AUDIT FLAGS: (1) SCOPE VIOLATION — commit includes docs/plugins.dct (13 lines of mid-session docket-event flush) despite explicit NOT-in-scope; content benign (today's PLG events), superseded by the orchestrator's end-of-session unload→commit→re-add; reinforces feedback_work_cycle_sonnet_guardrails (workers must stage per-file, never -A). (2) Worker burned most context debugging a TurnCache test interaction and its report omitted requested detail (distill prompt, tool_deps list) — recovered via direct diff audit instead."}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eafd5683f7fb29a640a0170e97ad6","type":"work_item","status":"in_progress","title":"B5: Integration + HITL — index scenario live, non-interference proof","description":"HITL exercises (user-driven, stop conditions per work-cycle conventions):\n1. Index loop: user asks chat LLM to drive a real Claude Code session → send → wake via PLUGIN_EVENT trigger → read_clean → chat LLM reports. Pass = full loop, no polling, wake message is one compact line (risk #8).\n2. Non-interference (comment #465): human drives the terminal agent directly with watch armed — zero dropped keystrokes, no viewport jumps; automated leg: PTY input recorder shows byte-identical child input watch-on vs watch-off.\n3. Mixed session: human + chat LLM interleave on one terminal; armed wake fires once at next turn end.\n4. Babysit smoke (comment #469): chat LLM answers a permission prompt per a user-given rubric via input_requested wake; A6 consecutive_fire_limit pauses after N exchanges and surfaces it.\n5. Exit paths: quit claude (agent_exited wake), close terminal mid-arm (terminal_closed), long turn (timed_out with screen).\nBlocked by Phase A (A1/A2/A6) + B1-B4. Pre-substrate prototyping allowed via mcp.proxy:minerva_terminal_* grants.","created_at":"2026-06-10T04:40:59","updated_at":"2026-06-10T22:31:01","priority":2,"tags":["agent-relay","hitl","phase-b"],"parent":"plugins.dct:019eafbe3360760b818b45fd663a2922"}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eafd57c6d701f9d1c68511cfc2b3d","type":"work_item","status":"in_progress","title":"B6: Marketplace packaging + release","description":"Add agent-relay to regen_registry.py PLUGIN_DIRS (hardcoded allow-list — codetools lesson); build linux/macos/windows targets (cross-build unsupported — run per-OS; remember the Windows install_only no-bin/ mkdir gotcha from codetools release); tag agent-relay-v0.1.0; registry regen + URL 302 checks + CI green; fresh install from marketplace on a clean profile: tools visible, skill seeded, grants applied (install-grants-all posture per DCR comment #470). Display name 'Agent Relay'. Gate: only after B5 HITL pass.","created_at":"2026-06-10T04:41:04","updated_at":"2026-06-10T06:44:33","priority":3,"tags":["agent-relay","marketplace","phase-b","release"],"parent":"plugins.dct:019eafbe3360760b818b45fd663a2922"}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb31f08697ecfa50c8c6f16ecc236","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"agent-relay: wait_turn long-poll tool — pull-based turn state for external MCP clients","description":"B5 HITL finding (owner, 2026-06-10): MCP is pull — external clients (Claude Code etc.) never receive the PLUGIN_EVENT push; that leg only wakes Minerva-internal chat LLMs. watch_status already exposes the state machine (watching/armed/last_wake_cause/last_turn_at/turn rows) but external clients must busy-poll it. Add minerva_agent_relay_wait_turn {terminal_id, timeout_ms} — blocks until the armed wake fires (or any turn end in all_turns mode) or timeout; returns the same payload as the event (cause, detection_method, turn rows) + timed_out flag. Worker already has the detection internally (condvar/poll on the watch session). Manifest tool addition → schema declare + /mcp reconnect after install. Component: agent-relay. Precedent: minerva_terminal_wait.","created_at":"2026-06-10T20:00:15","updated_at":"2026-06-10T22:30:49","tags":["B5-finding","agent-relay","mcp","relay-ux-suite"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb32faa4d7a2c8771543ab03798ec","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"agent-relay: persist profiles + filter rules to plugin data dir","description":"B5 HITL finding (2026-06-10): profile_set/filter_set are worker-memory only — every plugin restart silently reverts to seed profiles (live consequence: watch session matched with the stale ╰─╯ regex after a hot-swap and detected nothing, looked like a detector bug). Persist profiles + filter rules as JSON in the plugin data directory (scansort precedent for data-dir state), load at startup, seeds only when no file exists. Also: watch sessions die with the process — document that watch_start must be re-issued after restart (or persist+resume sessions, decide at implementation). Component: agent-relay.","created_at":"2026-06-10T20:18:25","updated_at":"2026-06-10T21:46:39","tags":["B5-finding","agent-relay","relay-ux-suite"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb333895f76d0a8398d5424cfbb7b","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"agent-relay: watch_status must record detection state even when emission is gated","description":"B5 HITL finding (2026-06-10): in notify_mode=armed, unarmed detected turns leave watch_status untouched (last_wake_cause/last_turn_at/detection_method stay null) because the state writes live inside the emission-gated maybe_emit path. Probe (fake host, all_turns) proved the detector fires settle_prompt on the real screen while the live armed-unarmed session showed nulls — cost us a debugging detour. Fix: record last_* detection fields on EVERY detection, independent of arming/emission; armed gate controls only the event. Status is the pull-side observability surface for external MCP clients (see wait_turn item 019eb31f0869) — it must tell the truth.","created_at":"2026-06-10T20:22:39","updated_at":"2026-06-10T21:05:31","tags":["B5-finding","agent-relay"],"resolution":"NOT A BUG — verified against source (watcher.rs:497-517): maybe_emit writes last_wake_cause/last_turn_at/last_detection_method/turn_end_row UNCONDITIONALLY before the notify-mode gate; only event emission is gated by arming. watch_status already records every detection, armed or not. The nulls observed during B5 that prompted this item were the NBSP prompt-regex failure (hint agent-relay/claude-prompt-nbsp) — detection wasn't firing at all, so there was no state to record. Closing as invalid; the pull-side observability gap that remains real is the lack of a BLOCKING wait_turn (item 019eb31f0869)."}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb345d4d972bf84c43a78cc8163f4","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"agent-relay: read_turn row window offset — snapshot includes input-box chrome rows","description":"B5 live finding (2026-06-10): turn boundaries now use absolute total_scrollback_rows (send snapshot → arm; detection → end), but the snapshot at send time counts the rows occupied by the live input box/UI chrome at screen bottom; when the answer arrives it renders INTO those rows while the box redraws lower. Net effect: read_turn(66→73) returned the post-answer chrome + the user's next draft instead of the answer (live repro: VT100 turn). Fix: anchor turn_start on the last CONTENT row, e.g. snapshot total_rows minus the trailing chrome/blank rows of the current viewport (or record the row of the echoed prompt when the send's echo appears). Verify with a live HITL turn: read_turn content must contain the agent's answer and not the next draft. Component: agent-relay.","created_at":"2026-06-10T20:42:38","updated_at":"2026-06-10T21:38:05","tags":["B5-finding","agent-relay","relay-ux-suite"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb35d52957a339ef7b7e6a64f3107","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"agent-relay: stateless detector fires on pre-existing idle screen — phantom turns + arm-consumption race","description":"B5 live finding (2026-06-10, reproduced deliberately): detector::run is pure content→verdict with no busy→idle transition memory, so (1) a fresh watch_start on an idle terminal registers a phantom turn_completed on its first wait cycle (status noise), and (2) the send→arm flow has a race: if a wait cycle samples the screen between arm() and the agent going busy (echo not yet rendered / 'esc to interrupt' not yet shown), the still-idle screen consumes the one-shot arm immediately — a false wake before the agent even starts. Not yet observed live in the armed path (turn output usually lands fast) but structurally possible, especially with the 300ms degraded-host pacing. Fix options: (a) track a busy-seen-since-arm flag — only emit turn_completed if the session observed a busy screen (esc-to-interrupt or output growth) after arming; (b) require total_rows growth beyond the arm snapshot before a turn_completed counts. Option (a)+(b) combined is robust. Also surfaces in watch_status as phantom last_turn_at right after watch_start. Related: watch_timeout_ms=600000 reaps idle sessions after 10 min by design — document in skill so chat LLMs re-watch_start (or arm refreshes the timeout).","created_at":"2026-06-10T21:08:18","updated_at":"2026-06-10T21:37:57","tags":["B5-finding","agent-relay","detection","relay-ux-suite"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb3616292706685232a7ce81b354e","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"agent-relay: relay_ask — the whole index loop as one blocking tool call","description":"UX-suite item (owner-approved 2026-06-10). New tool minerva_agent_relay_relay_ask {terminal_id, text, timeout_ms?, distill?, model_spec?} = send + arm + BLOCK until the armed turn ends (or timeout/agent_exited/terminal_closed) + read_turn, returning {answer/content, cause, detection_method, timed_out, truncated}. Turns \"ask the terminal agent\" into a function call for pull-only external MCP clients (Claude Code etc.) — no polling, no watch lifecycle management. Composes existing code: send handler + an internal blocking wait on the session's wake (condvar/poll), then read_turn. Subsumes wait_turn (019eb31f0869) for the common case — implement wait_turn as the monitoring-only primitive in the same pass (relay_ask = send + wait_turn + read_turn). MANIFEST ADDITION → full schema declare + reinstall + /mcp reconnect. Depends on: busy-gate (019eb35d5295) for correctness of the blocking wake; read_turn row fix (019eb345d4d9) for answer quality. Tool description must state the blocking semantics + sensible default timeout (suggest 120s, max 600s like exec).","created_at":"2026-06-10T21:12:44","updated_at":"2026-06-10T22:30:45","tags":["agent-relay","relay-ux-suite"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb3617c387dc186a698b92fdf0b6e","type":"work_item","status":"done","title":"agent-relay: self-managing watch lifecycle — arm refreshes reap timer, sessions resume on restart","description":"UX-suite item (owner-approved 2026-06-10). Watches become an implementation detail, not a user-managed lifecycle: (1) arm() refreshes the watch_timeout_ms reap timer — an armed session never self-reaps mid-turn; the 10-min reap applies only to idle UNARMED watches (live incident: session reaped silently between demos, user's turn ran unwatched). (2) Watch sessions persist (terminal_id, profile_id, notify_mode) to the plugin data dir and RESUME on plugin start — owns the \"persist+resume sessions\" decision deferred in 019eb32faa4d (profiles/filters persistence; implement together: one state file, load at startup). (3) watch_start stays for explicit passive monitoring; send/relay_ask auto-start remains the primary path. (4) Skill text updated: drop the re-watch_start babysitting instruction once this lands. Verify: restart plugin mid-watch → session resumes and detects the next turn without any re-setup.","created_at":"2026-06-10T21:12:50","updated_at":"2026-06-10T21:46:34","tags":["agent-relay","relay-ux-suite"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019eb37828537bd1aab5094bf30554fb","type":"hint","status":"draft","title":"agent-relay/tui-busy-block-collapses","created_at":"2026-06-10T21:37:36","updated_at":"2026-06-10T21:37:36","value":"Claude Code's busy block (spinner + status area) can occupy MORE scrollback rows than the final answer layout — the tail of the screen REDRAWS and shrinks, so \"new output renders at >= rows-at-time-T\" is FALSE for any T after the write. Turn-start anchors must snapshot BEFORE writing (pre-write screen is stable; the redraw region starts at the input box). Post-write snapshots race the busy block and read_turn misses the answer.","component":"agent-relay","key":"tui-busy-block-collapses"}
